docs.lead_paragraph: HUDSON RIVER RAILROAD.--The citizens of the Nineteenth and Twentieth Wards, and particularly owners of property along the Eleventh-avenue, who are opposed to the use of steam as a motive power on the Hudson River Railroad, below Sixtieth-street, assembled on masse, on Wednesday evening, at the house of Mr. DONNELLY, corner of Eleventh-avenue and Forty-Seventh-street, to take into consideration the best means of attaining that object.

docs.lead_paragraph: Three hundred and sixty-five days are a long while for this fast age. The world and all its matters ought to make wonderful progress towards perfection, if they really move at the rapid rate that we generally think they do.

docs.lead_paragraph: By telegraph from Charleston, we learn that Mr. KING had arrived at Key West by the steamship Fulton, on the 22d inst. He was intending to remain there a few days, perhaps for a longer time.

headline.main: Later from Havana and Key West--Arrival of the Isabel at Charleston--Hon. Mr. W. R. King at Key West.

docs.lead_paragraph: The steamer Isabel has arrived at this port, having left Havana and Key West on the 22d inst. Small pox had disappeared from Havana. The steam ship Futon arrived at Key West on the 22d. Mr. KING'S health was better than when he left Norfolk he would remain several days at Key West if the climate proved agreeable.

headline.main: THE MECHANICS' INSTITUTE.; Office, Appropriate Culture, and Duty of the Mechanic. A LECTURE BY HON. GEO. BANCROFT.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Fifth Lecture of the course before the Mechanics' Institute was delivered last evening by Hon. GEO. BANCROFT. The lecture-room was in sufficient to accommodate all who attended, and several were obliged to stand at the door leading from the Library.

docs.lead_paragraph: From the London Daily News. It is not often that we are treated with a morsel of amusing and innocent gossip in direct connection with political affairs; but such a treat is furnished to us now in the replies of the American Foreign Ministers to inquiries from their own State Department, about the sufficiency or insufficiency of their salaries to maintain them at foreign courts.

docs.lead_paragraph: Senator CLEMENS has received a dispatch, stating that Mr. KING arrived at Key West on the 22d instant--his health being no better than when he left- that he has himself lost all hope of his recovery, and will remain at Key West.

docs.lead_paragraph: REPORTS OF COMMITTEE. Mr. COOLEY, from commerce and navigation, by bill, giving the Staten Island. Railroad Company ferry privileges between New-York and Staten Island. Mr. MONROE gave notice of a bill amending the act for the preservation of the public health.
